{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537125","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537125"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:13:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:13:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15907"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15907"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.43,0.39,0.11,0.01,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8598"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105937"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8598"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15907"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88412"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"265"},{"type":"tags","id":"1685"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20601"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36653"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38904"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105937"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 36-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with his partner due to difficulty conceiving for 18 months. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He works as a long-distance truck driver and smokes 15 cigarettes per day. He drinks approximately eight standard drinks of alcohol per week. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Genital examination reveals a grade II varicocele on the left side. Semen analysis reveals a sperm count of 12 million/mL (15-200), with 25% progressive motility (\u0026gt;32%) and 5% normal morphology (\u0026gt;4%).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following factors is most likely contributing to these semen analysis results?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cigarette smoking","Varicocele","Prolonged sitting","Age","Alcohol consumption"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with oligozoospermia (reduced sperm count) and asthenozoospermia (reduced motility) on semen analysis. Among the risk factors presented, a \u003Cstrong\u003Evaricocele\u003C/strong\u003E is most likely to cause these specific findings. Varicoceles affect approximately 15% of men and up to 40% of men with infertility. They impair spermatogenesis through increased testicular temperature and oxidative stress, typically causing reduced sperm count and motility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECigarette smoking\u003C/strong\u003E can affect sperm quality through oxidative stress and DNA damage, but typically causes leukocytospermia, or the presence of an abnormally high number of white cells in the semen. While smoking cessation should be encouraged, it is less likely than the varicocele to be the primary cause of these specific findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcohol consumption\u003C/strong\u003E at the level described (eight standard drinks per week) is unlikely to significantly impact fertility. More severe alcohol consumption (\u0026gt;14 drinks per week) would be needed to cause significant changes in semen parameters. Moderate to heavy alcohol consumption is also more likely to be associated with abnormal sperm morphology (teratozoospermia) rather than low sperm count and motility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProlonged sitting\u003C/strong\u003E associated with his occupation as a truck driver could theoretically affect spermatogenesis through increased scrotal temperature. However, this effect would be less pronounced than that of a varicocele, which causes continuous venous congestion and heat stress.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAge\u003C/strong\u003E is not a significant factor in this case, as the patient is 36 years old. While sperm parameters do decline with age, significant changes typically occur after age 40.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement in this scenario would be consideration of varicocele repair, which has been shown to improve semen parameters in properly selected patients. Additionally, lifestyle optimisation should be encouraged and the patient should be informed that\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Varicoceles are strongly associated with male infertility, and treatment can reduce male infertility.","Smoking and alcohol consumption are modifiable risk factors that can significantly impact sperm quality.","Elevated scrotal temperature from prolonged sitting can impair spermatogenesis."],"references":["Agarwal A, Cannarella R, Saleh RA, Boitrelle F, Gul M, Tuncay Toprak, et al. Impact of Varicocele Repair on Semen Parameters in Infertile Men: A Systematic Review and Meta-Analysis. The World Journal of Men\u2019s Health. 2022 Oct 28;41(2):289\u20139.","Durairajanayagam D. Lifestyle causes of male infertility. Arab J Urol. 2018 Feb 13;16(1):10-20. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5922227/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88412"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15907"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88412"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-15T08:13:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-15T08:16:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8598"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105937"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Sexual Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt